data.content:
Your test works but uses generic `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere, which produces unhelpful failure messages like "Expected: True, Actual: False." MSTest 3.x+ has specialized collection assertions with much better diagnostics:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Specific assertions → clear failure messages
    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.Contains(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users);
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Your code | Modern equivalent | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Failure says "collection was empty" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Failure says "Expected count: 3, Actual: 2" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(admin)` | Failure says "value was null" |

If you only expect **one** admin, `Assert.ContainsSingle` is even better — it returns the element and fails with a clear message if there are 0 or 2+:

```csharp
var admin = Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
Assert.IsTrue(admin.IsActive);
```

These require **MSTest 3.8+** (the `MSTest` metapackage or `MSTest.Sdk`).
